issue.title: C#: Avoid inefficient DenseTensor ctor in ToTensor extensions

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: 

Constructing DenseTensor using System.Array is inefficient as it involves boxing/unboxing for every value. We have an internal constructor for DenseTensor that takes System.Array that is used by the `ToTensor` methods in ArrayTensorExtensions. 

Update the extension methods to only use the inefficient ctor if they cannot flatten the input array directly (no boxing/unboxing if it can) and construct a DenseTensor with a `Memory<T>` around that copy.

Add extension method for 4D array. Assuming that is somewhat common if you have NCHW input.

I did a basic perf test of creating a DenseTensor and populating it via operator[] with indices and doing so is roughly equivalent to directly populating a 1D array, so that path to creating a DenseTensor is okay (and our existing samples which setup input that way are fine).

Misc: Fix some long lines 

**Motivation and Context**
#1652 and recurring issues with unexpected performance when constructing a DenseTensor from an existing multidimensional C# array.
